<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much water does a lawn need per week?", answer: "Most lawns need 1 to 1.5 inches of water per week during the growing season, including rainfall. One inch over a 1,000 sq ft lawn equals 623 gallons. A 5,000 sq ft lawn needs about 3,100 gallons per week at 1 inch. Warm-season grasses like bermudagrass are more drought-tolerant and can get by on 0.75 inch; cool-season grasses in summer may need 1.5 to 2 inches in very hot weather." },
  { question: "How long should I run my sprinklers?", answer: "Divide the gallons needed by your sprinkler's gallons per minute (GPM). A typical oscillating sprinkler puts out 3 to 5 GPM; in-ground zones vary from 8 to 20 GPM. To deliver 623 gallons to a 1,000 sq ft area with a 4 GPM sprinkler, run it 156 minutes per week, split into 2 or 3 sessions. The calculator shows this automatically when you enter a GPM value." },
  { question: "How often should I water my lawn?", answer: "Twice a week is usually better than daily. Deep, infrequent watering encourages grass roots to grow down rather than out, making the lawn more drought-tolerant. In cooler weather, once a week is enough. In extreme heat, 3 times a week. Water early morning (5-9 AM) to minimize evaporation and avoid leaving leaves wet overnight, which encourages disease." },
  { question: "How do I know if my lawn needs water?", answer: "Walk across the lawn. If the grass springs back, it is fine. If footprints remain visible, the grass is water-stressed and needs water soon. Another test: push a screwdriver into the soil. If it goes in easily to 6 inches, moisture is adequate. If you hit hard resistance at 2 or 3 inches, the soil is drying out." },
  { question: "Do smart sprinkler controllers save water?", answer: "Yes, typically 15 to 30 percent. Smart controllers use local weather data and soil moisture to skip watering after rain, reduce run times in cool weather, and extend them in heatwaves. EPA WaterSense certified models are independently tested. The payback period is usually 1 to 3 years in metered water areas." }
]) %>

